						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> I usually code a few routines that take care of that part right away, and all the heavy work is actually put on the game logic. So once you're past that, you can experiment with the actual game engine and see what works best for you. </div><br /><br />Yes, I see what you mean.  Recently I did the same thing on the DS. I made some code to be able to do a an infinite map (like a world map in FF) and it was working well.  I just put the project on the ice because I don't have much interest in the DS these days.  I went back to my favorite platform, the nes, and I gave it a go.  No I hope to go somewhere.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">About the CS3 comment, well, I code in AS3 (which BTW is much better than AS2) sometimes, but I don't use Flash, I compile my code with the free Flex SDK. This means that I have *zero* debugging capabilities (not even "trace" works), but it isn't so bad, since I'm used to 6502 asm! =)</div>
<br />
<br />I don't really use AS2 by choice, more because of a third party library which doesn't support AS3... Because of that technical limitation, we are stuck int AS2. And it's a one shot project which I had to learn all about the fun (...) of flash in very limited time.
<br />
<br />I hope that you use the free IDE flashDevelop, it really save you a lot of time.  It interface is very similar to visual studio.
<br />
<br />As for debugging, in your situation I would suggest you to create a debug panel that contains the information you want to trace. Worst case, if the space is limited, you can always send some data to another external flash object  or even sent it to the html page.</div>

