					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">My only concern is if the technical documents could be  wrong in the first place then it make it even harder to understand how to use it.<br /><br />For example, in my problem, I didn't understand why to update the PPU_CTRL during a scroll in blarg's tentative tutorial.  When I read the doc on the nes wiki (and nestech), this is what I found:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">76543210<br />||||||||<br />||||||++- Base nametable address<br />||||||&nbsp; &nbsp; &#40;0 = $2000; 1 = $2400; 2 = $2800; 3 = $2C00&#41;<br />++++++--- Other</div><br /><br />nowhere is it written that bit 0 and 1 are for the MSB of the X and Y scroll location like Tepple mentioned above (which I'm grateful that he mentioned it).  Now, is it because the document is wrong or some information is missing?</div><br />The two interpretations of bits 0 and 1 are equivalent because of the way scrolling works. From below, in the "Nametables" section:<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The NES has four nametables, arranged in a 2x2 pattern. Each occupies a 1 KB chunk of PPU address space, starting at $2000 at the top left, $2400 at the top right, $2800 at the bottom left, and $2C00 at the bottom right.</div>
<br />But yes, it's a good idea to include both interpretations of bits 0 and 1. I've made this edit in the PPU article on the wiki; thanks for the idea. If you find something unclear, you can always register on the wiki and post in an article's talk page.</div>

